Rating: 3
this was a very moist and light cake. And yes very crumbly. I also boiled the crannberries in a little Grand Marnier and water with a little orange zest and a dash of nutmeg. I layered some of the topping in the cake with the rest on top. My whole family liked the cake and since my teenage son had 2 big pieces I would definetely make it again. Maybe next time for guests.

Rating: 0
An easy, quick and tasty cake, and best of all, my friends thought it was delicious! If using dried cranberries (Cranraisins worked well) always hydrate in boiling water for less than a minute. Also, I added the zest of a half a lemon which perked things up. Lastly, I sprinkled half the sugar,cinnamon, walnut mixture in the bottom of the pan, then the other half sprinkle on top of batter, pressing down to adhere. It's a keeper.

Rating: 0
This is a good recipe and I would absolutely make it again. A few notes I had, I used a tablespoon of cinnamon and poured all the sugar into the cake itself. Also don't use prepackaged dried cranberries! They are so dry and only hurt this recipe. Use bulk cranberries that aren't dried to a crisp, the taste is SO much better that way. Happy eating!!

Rating: 3
This recipe makes a moist and sweet cake. I used Splenda in place of the sugar and since I did not have buttermilk, I used 1 T. of lemon juice added to 8 oz. of skim milk. I agree the cake crumbles easily but it tastes good and the cranberries make a pretty presentation.

